This quarter brought new details about how exactly Amazon will access this =
market without blowing up its profitability. The first way is exactly what =
you would expect: Amazon believes that being involved in more purchase deci=
sions will ensure they get the big-ticket items too. Jassy said in answer t=
o an analyst question:

When you look at the split between revenue growth and unit growth, you do s=
ee some impact of the lower ASP products that we=E2=80=99re selling as well=
 as some of the trade down that consumers are doing. But we take that as a =
real positive, seeing the growth in everyday essential categories, which ar=
e really predicated on speed. So you have to have fast delivery to be able =
to sell the those products to customers. And when you do, it results in a s=
tickier consumer relationship, higher orders, building larger baskets, whic=
h help our ship economics, and repeat orders are stronger. So those are all=
 positive signs, and we=E2=80=99ll take any short-term degradation in ASP b=
ecause what we=E2=80=99re focused on primarily is free cash flow here. And =
we see the ability to unlock all new elements of the consumer spend.

Second, most of these everyday essentials =E2=80=94 and in contrast to larg=
er-ticket items =E2=80=94 are first-party, not third-party. Jassy said in r=
esponse to a question about the declining share of third-party unit mix:

Third-party sellers, yes, the percent of paid units was 60% in Q3. And if y=
ou look over the last two years, it=E2=80=99s =E2=80=94 essentially, it was=
 at 59%, stepping up to 60%, stepping up to 61% pretty much every second qu=
arter. So what we=E2=80=99re seeing is still in a tight band between 59% an=
d 61%. But what we=E2=80=99re seeing is the impact of the everyday essentia=
ls. 3P demand is still strong and unit volumes are strong. It=E2=80=99s jus=
t the everyday essentials tend to skew more to 1P than 3P.

To step back, first-party means that Amazon buys the product from the manuf=
acturer and then sells it to the customer. This means that both the entire =
price of the item and the cost of the item are on the income statement. Thi=
rd-party means that the seller lists their product on Amazon, and either ha=
ndles fulfillment themselves or, more likely, pays to have Amazon hold thei=
r inventory and fulfill orders. Those third-party sellers could be the manu=
facturers, or they could be another wholesaler or retailer.

There are a number of reasons why it makes sense that everyday essentials a=
re more likely to be first-party rather than third-party. First, everyday e=
ssential manufacturers are probably less likely to be equipped to be retail=
ers in their own right; think CPG companies like P&G and Unilever that are =
used to distributing their goods through retailers, both online and off. Se=
cond, by cutting out any other middlemen Amazon keeps all of the available =
margin, which is beneficial given that these are relatively cheap items. Th=
ird, because these are everyday essentials, Amazon likely wants total contr=
ol over inventory so they can assure they are distributed across their netw=
ork to enable same-day or one-day delivery. Fourth, given the very high tur=
nover in these items, there probably isn=E2=80=99t much money to be made fr=
om warehouse charges anyways. Fifth, these items are probably less likely t=
o command as much advertising dollars, another way in which Amazon makes mo=
ney off of third-party sellers; indeed, even if advertising dollars were av=
ailable, capturing the full benefit of these items entails making them as e=
asy to buy as possible.

The third detail about this business was the talking points Amazon shared a=
bout a new facility in Shreveport, Louisiana that just launched that is far=
 more automated than anything Amazon has built yet. Jassy said in his prepa=
red remarks:

We continue to innovate in robotics to speed delivery, lower cost to serve,=
 and further improve safety in our fulfillment network. We recently launche=
d our 12th-generation fulfillment center design with the first building lau=
nching in Shreveport, Louisiana. This is the first facility that incorporat=
es our newest robotics inventions that simplify stowing, picking, packing, =
and shipping processes. Thus far, this new design reduces fulfillment proce=
ssing time by up to 25%, increases the number of items we can offer for sam=
e-day or next-day delivery and is expected to drive a 25% improvement in ou=
r cost to serve during peak within this next generation facility. Though we=
 believe we have more expansive automation and robotics than other retail p=
eers, it=E2=80=99s still early days in how much automation we expect in our=
 fulfillment network.

Jassy added in an answer later in the call:

The reason why we=E2=80=99re trying to have more robotics and automation in=
 our fulfillment network is it allows us to ship more quickly, to ship more=
 cost effectively, and to make conditions even safer for our fulfillment te=
ammates than what they already have today. And I think something that the t=
eam has done in a very disciplined way, and I talked about this a little bi=
t in my annual letter, my shareholder letter is just they have been very th=
oughtful about defining what are the primitive foundational building blocks=
 that you need, that you can then use in lots of different combinations to =
build additional automation/robotics capabilities down the road, so we can =
move even more quickly with the next generation of robotics capabilities. A=
nd that team has invested in those and they=E2=80=99re already working on t=
he next generation.

This is almost certainly the most important component in terms of controlli=
ng expense growth in the long run. Every involvement of human pickers or pa=
ckers is a marginal cost that provides a floor in terms of what Amazon can =
sell profitably; to the extent that Amazon can continue to replace humans w=
ith robots, whose marginal cost is basically electricity, is the extent the=
y can offer ever lower-priced everyday essentials profitably. Of course the=
y still have to deliver them, but that is where the self-driving cars and d=
rones come in!

What is interesting is how this mirrors so many of Amazon=E2=80=99s other b=
uild-outs in the past. Way back when Amazon Logistics was just a rumor I wr=
ote in an Update ( https://stratechery.com/2016/dropbox-leaves-aws-should-u=
ps-and-fedex-be-afraid/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0=
ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS=
5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7I=
nVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDE2L2Ryb3Bib3gtbGVhdmVzLWF3cy1z=
aG91bGQtdXBzLWFuZC1mZWRleC1iZS1hZnJhaWQvIl19LCJleHAiOjE3MzM5MjMzMTAsImlhdCI=
6MTczMTMzMTMxMCwiaXNzIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9hcGkucGFzc3BvcnQub25saW5lL29hdXRoIiwic2=
NvcGUiOiJmZWVkOnJlYWQgYXJ0aWNsZTpyZWFkIGFzc2V0OnJlYWQgY2F0ZWdvcnk6cmVhZCBlb=
