It seems likely that Amazon will build out this network from the inside out=
, by first connecting its fulfillment centers with each other and with supp=
liers, leaving the more logistically challenging and expensive last mile de=
livery to whomever wants to fight for it. That doesn=E2=80=99t sound great =
for UPS=E2=80=99 already low e-commerce margins.

That=E2=80=99s exactly what happened, and, over time, Amazon has pushed fur=
ther and further into the last mile, which means that UPS and USPS are stuc=
k with the least profitable deliveries while Amazon has internalized the re=
st.

The way this is poised to play out in terms of Amazon=E2=80=99s sales is a =
little different. For many years Amazon has been increasing the number of t=
hird-party sales, which really give Amazon the best of both worlds: they ge=
t way more selection, and they have much higher margins because they=E2=80=
=99re basically running a services business, charging for everything from w=
arehousing to discovery via advertising to transactions to delivery. I don=
=E2=80=99t think they=E2=80=99re going to really move into those markets th=
at are already dominated by third-party sellers. At the same time, I expect=
 that this expansion of first-party goods will continue to increase, partic=
ularly as the marginal cost of fulfilling them drops thanks to robotics. Th=
e end result will be that everything with high turnover is first party, and=
 everything with low turnover is third party, which is to say Amazon will m=
aximize its profitability for both.

